I am 75/75 stars in Arcade and 121/150 in Pro mode. Here is my review so far.   I paid $3 for this and even that was to much. Here's why. While the graphics are good and having to use the right weapon to combat mobs special powers is good. What makes this game truly hard is your own tower's AI. Most TD games the towers will prioritize low health or enemies nearest the exit. Not this game. No, your towers seem to pick at random and sometimes, especially on mobs that heal, your towers won't even finish off the target before switching to another. It is incredibly frustrating.   I have a basic knowledge of programming and it seems to me the towers calculate how many times they must fire to kill a target and do not do an if/then check before switching to the next target. I know the game has the ability to check the status of targets because heavy guns will break shields and switch to the next target with shields. So their must be some sort of check for shields going on there in the AI. Why the Devs did not include this same sort of check to make sure an enemy is dead before a tower switches seems like a big oversight and one that makes the game irritating.

The game looks quite slick and for the most part is a serviceable for passing the time while you're waiting in lines or whatever. As many others have pointed out, the game mechanics and balance are VERY poorly designed, it almost looks like they created the levels (chapters) by playtesting them with a single solution - the only one that works. As a result, the game can get extremely frustrating as the only way to discover the exact placement and purchase of units is to play through the chapter several times until you figure it out. A slight misplacement of a unit during wave 1 can make winning impossible by wave 10. That's just bad game design and nothing else. There are also some frustrating bugs with regard to unit placement. That said, almost all the android TD games out there are pretty bad in one way or another, but this one is a real disappointment. due to the huge number of bugs. It also lacks a grid, making unit placement painful. There's no reason not to have a hex grid overlay.  To the devs- if you can't playtest the game on paper with counters then don't bother writing the code. Get the rules and movement sorted out first before you write code and do graphics.

I'm 9 levels in, and there are a TON of options on attacking a level.  To try them all to becomes tedious and time-wasting.  For my own sanity I've given up.    For what I paid, I got my money's worth, but I could have had so much fun with it.

Pretty average in terms of a tower defense game. It then is held back by several things. The maps don't seem to take into consideration the range of the starter towers and mob pathing or the tiles the guns take up. I found very frequently I'd place a standard gun on a u-turn then need a flame tower on the next wave. There's not enough room on the same corner for both guns and placing it on another bend did nothing as the minions pathed outside of its range on that particular corner forcing me to restart the level.  The turret targeting AI is also done poorly as minions would frequently escape range due to my turret switching to a closer target on the other side of the road rather than the one further along the path. I also found the damage the turrets do to be a little arbitrary. Anti-air guns would take 3 shots to kill a flying minion but the second shot would leave him with almost no health. This would be fine if the standard turret could assist on air units, but they can't.   Save your money.

This is a decent game. The graphics are good, it loads quickly and game play is smooth. Currently running this on the droid turbo 2 and there have been no problems. In general, I enjoy playing the game, but here are a few of the things I've noted that other players may or may not care about.  Tower Variety: There is a good variety of towers to pick from, each tower is specialized for a certain type of unit.  Basically, for each kind of enemy, there's exactly one tower that's specialized to kill it. Try to use any other tower and it simply won't be effective (with some exceptions).   Path Predictability: The game doesn't do well describing what units are coming from different paths. You have to replay a wave after watching it to know how to place your towers, otherwise you lose.  AI: No control over what unit a tower focuses on. Often, towers obviously focus on the wrong unit allowing others to escape that normally wouldn't (and it's painful to watch).

If it wasn't for the excellent music and the great unit visual design, I would have given the game just 1 star.  The gameplay is awfully scripted: you can only win by following exactly what the level designer had planned for you to do. You have to place exactly the correct tower in exactly the correct spot and do exactly the correct upgrade at exactly the correct time or else you stand no chance, and you usually have just enough money to do only the correct thing at the correct time. Absolutely no space allowed for creativity whatsoever, it's just a matter of figuring out what the level designer had in mind, usually through trial and error. This is mainly the result of having a very narrow and strict one-to-one enemy type to counter-tower relationship.  A terrible design decision really. Also the tower upgrades are pretty boring and offer no variety unlike some of the other better TD games out there.  The fact that after all this I gave the game 3 starts speaks volumes about how good the music and the unit visual design are.

This attractive TD game just misses too many basics for me to recommend.  For one, the towers and upgrades you research between rounds have a pre-defined order to them.  You can't decide what to research.  Next, tower targetting is just awful.  Towers will choose a new target that's just entering it's range rather than the one that's closest to the goal.  It ends up letting so many enemies by that it could have easily killed.  Finally, as a number of other people have mentioned a large part of the game is "guess which tower the developer wants you to put here".  A lot of levels require specific towers to be placed in a specific order to win.  Overall, it's pretty but there are far better TD games out there.

I really wanted to like this game. But there is no difficulty setting. That translates into Extremely difficult game play, ALWAYS being STARVED for cash and no ability to sell turrets means there is often only ONE way to win.  Figuring that out too often means playing the most recent 3 levels over and over again. New arcade mode helps a little but the game is just FAR too stingy and unfolds far too slowly.

tower upgrades are linear; you have 1 star, you can upgrade the next thing we tell you. There's a "restart wave" button that I thought was cool at first, until I realized this is because if you do not place the Exact tower the dev expects you to for the next enemy type in the Exact right spot, you will lose every time. Tower enemy-selection AI is spotty at best... There's an enemy farther along but it shoots further-away enemies first? Awful. Towers do not prioritize the best enemy type to shoot, so you finally saved up to get a $600 rocket tower? Expect it to shoot trash nearby and not the big mechs that will keep walking right though. Very frustrating and very disappointing for a game in "Top Paid" strategy.

content: All those winers saying this game isn't balanced need to go play some Battletoads.   The graphics are top notch. The challenge is there even if the action/stages seem a little shallow. To be fair I am on level five chapter one. For 2.99 you get great graphics and 50 total levels so there is good value.   The real reason I bought this game is the Developers seem to be reading the comments and responding to ensure player satisfaction, and that to me is indicative of quality.  The game is more puzzle than tower defense, as once you set the towers there is not very much interaction left as you wait for the outcome.  I will update as the I progress through the game. content: For all you TD game lovers out there, THIS is a must play game !

After reading some of the reviews I was worried that this was going to be a pay to win game even after purchasing it but I'm happy to report it's not so!   It's a little different from the normal td games because there's a lot fewer tower slots but it makes it challenging and needs strategy to complete with all stars.  These stars you use to unlock more towers.  Love the versatility in the towers and the ease of restarting waves to change strategies.   Thanks for a great game!  Support these devs!

Firstly, I find it highly unballanced, especially compared to the previous Epic War TD which I loved. Being stuck with an X number of building slots on each map is again not pleasant from a TD player's point of view, and the upgrade style is very  very bad.  Another intersting thing: your blue cannon tower? It does NOT shoot
replyContent:
Unfortunately, you wont find a perfect TD. I bet your favorite one still has negative ratings. Some players like limited tower's slots, some don't. 
This time, we wanted to add a bit of a puzzle into the TD genre. Try to give it a second chance:)P.s I think you are speaking about Anti-Air tower. It is marked with "wings" and only shoots air units.
